  1633‚Üí### Testing
  1635‚Üí`Result` instances have two unsafe methods, aptly called `_unsafeUnwrap` and `_unsafeUnwrapErr` which **should only be used in a test environment**.
  1636‚Üí
  1637‚Üí`_unsafeUnwrap` takes a `Result<T, E>` and returns a `T` when the result is an `Ok`, otherwise it throws a custom object.
  1638‚Üí
  1639‚Üí`_unsafeUnwrapErr` takes a `Result<T, E>` and returns a `E` when the result is an `Err`, otherwise it throws a custom object.
  1640‚Üí
  1641‚ÜíThat way you can do something like:
  1642‚Üí
  1643‚Üí```typescript
  1644‚Üíexpect(myResult._unsafeUnwrap()).toBe(someExpectation)
  1645‚Üí```
  1646‚Üí
  1647‚ÜíHowever, do note that `Result` instances are comparable. So you don't necessarily need to unwrap them in order to assert expectations in your tests. So you could also do something like this:
  1648‚Üí
  1649‚Üí```typescript
  1650‚Üíimport { ok } from 'neverthrow'
  1651‚Üí
  1652‚Üí// ...
  1653‚Üí
  1654‚Üíexpect(callSomeFunctionThatReturnsAResult("with", "some", "args")).toEqual(ok(someExpectation));
  1655‚Üí```
  1656‚Üí
  1657‚ÜíBy default, the thrown value does not contain a stack trace. This is because stack trace generation [makes error messages in Jest harder to understand](https://github.com/supermacro/neverthrow/pull/215). If you want stack traces to be generated, call `_unsafeUnwrap` and / or `_unsafeUnwrapErr` with a config object:
  1658‚Üí
  1659‚Üí```typescript
  1660‚Üí_unsafeUnwrapErr({
  1661‚Üí  withStackTrace: true,
  1662‚Üí})
  1663‚Üí
  1664‚Üí// ^ Now the error object will have a `.stack` property containing the current stack
  1665‚Üí```
  1666‚Üí
  1667‚Üí---
  1668‚Üí
  1669‚ÜíIf you find this package useful, please consider [sponsoring me](https://github.com/sponsors/supermacro/) or simply [buying me a coffee](https://ko-fi.com/gdelgado)!
  1670‚Üí
  1671‚Üí---
  1672‚Üí
  1673‚Üí## A note on the Package Name
  1675‚ÜíAlthough the package is called `neverthrow`, please don't take this literally. I am simply encouraging the developer to think a bit more about the ergonomics and usage of whatever software they are writing.
  1676‚Üí
  1677‚Üí`Throw`ing and `catching` is very similar to using `goto` statements - in other words; it makes reasoning about your programs harder. Secondly, by using `throw` you make the assumption that the caller of your function is implementing `catch`. This is a known source of errors. Example: One dev `throw`s and another dev uses the function without prior knowledge that the function will throw. Thus, and edge case has been left unhandled and now you have unhappy users, bosses, cats, etc.
  1678‚Üí
  1679‚ÜíWith all that said, there are definitely good use cases for throwing in your program. But much less than you might think.
  1680‚Üí
  1681‚Üí### License
  1683‚ÜíThe neverthrow project is available as open source under the terms of the [MIT license](https://github.com/supermacro/neverthrow/blob/master/LICENSE).

